VALUES (175, 'Knee Break Ankle Mobilization Video Exercise Guide', 'Calves', 'Warmup', 'Bodyweight', 'Compound',
        'Dynamic Stretching', 'Beginner', 'None', 'The knee break ankle mobilization is a dynamic stretching drill used to increase the mobility of your ankles.
Ankle mobility is extremely important when performing lower body exercises such as the squat, leg press, and deadlift.
Utilize the knee break ankle mobilization as part of your warm up routine before your leg workouts.', 'In an upright position, position a plate underneath the upper portion of your foot.
Keep your torso erect but bend the knees and allow the ankles to flex as your weight is shifted slightly forward.
Once you run out of range of motion in your ankles, extend the knees back to the start position.
Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.', 'Experiment with moving dynamically over one leg versus another or shifting side to side once the knees are bent.
Once you reach end range, focus on contracting the muscle on the anterior portion of your shin (tibialis anterior) to improve control through that new range of motion.
As you progress into using this stretch more routinely, try to resist looking down and learn to control position through kinesthetic awareness rather than visual input.',
        'https://www.youtube.com/embed/KngATp2V7kc?rel=0',
        'https://cdn.muscleandstrength.com/sites/default/files/knee-break-ankle-mobilization.jpg');
INSERT INTO exercise(id, name, target_muscle_group, exercise_type, equipment_required, mechanics, forcetype,
                     experience_level, secondary_muscles, overview, instructions, tips, video, image)
VALUES (176, 'Peroneal Foam Rolling Video Exercise Guide', 'Calves', 'SMR', 'Foam Roll', 'Isolation', 'Compression',
        'Beginner', 'None', 'Foam rolling your peroneals is a great way to warm up and cool down for your workout, especially if you plan to perform lower body exercises that require the calves to be more mobile.
When you foam roll the peroneals, or any muscle group for that matter, you alleviate some of the tension that is built up during the day and your workouts.', 'In a side lying position, place the foam roller directly underneath your thigh between your knee and hip.
Support your upper body using your forearm and free hand. Adjust pressure into the roller with your free hand and foot.
Slowly roll up and down the length of the peroneals while slightly rotating the leg periodically for 20-30 seconds.
Repeat on the other side.', 'The most important thing you can remember with any soft tissue work: KEEP BREATHING. Don’t hold your breath, you want to release tension, not generate it.
Do not allow yourself to fall into overextension, keep tension through the abs.
If you find a tender spot, pause for 5-6 seconds and focus on slow, deep breaths and try to relax.
Foam rolling may be uncomfortable but that’s not an excuse to avoid it. It hurts because there may be physiological or neurological influences generating a pain response. The more you roll the better it’ll feel provided there’s no serious underlying mechanism.
Be careful when you roll near the head of the fibula (just below the base of the knee) as the common peroneal nerve passes through this region and can become aggravated.
Don’t slump into the shoulder capsule, maintain an active upper body.
If you notice any burning, numbness, or tingling, keep moving past that area. It’s likely a nerve and pausing on it for any length of time would not be a good idea.
If you find a sensitive spot, pause for a second and take the joint through flexion and extension. This a method of active release known as “tack and floss”.',
        'https://www.youtube.com/embed/y6zQQglFFMo?rel=0',
        'https://cdn.muscleandstrength.com/sites/default/files/foam-rolling-peroneals.jpg');
